{
  "texts": [
    "A very likely scenario is continued pretraining, where the data leaked by users is treated as an in-domain corpus (and thus given more influence than pretraining data).",
    "This procedure is known to improve models' performances in the leaked domains (Gururangan et al., 2020).",
    "Notably, Shi and Lipani (2023) find that fine-tuning a model on in-domain text enriched by textual instructions leads to an increase in the model performance even if gold labels are not shown to the model.",
    "This setup perfectly matches the kind of data shown to chat LLMs when evaluated by researchers.",
    "This means that closed-source LLMs such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can make use of these gold standard examples from widely used NLP benchmarks to gain an unfair advantage over other models."
  ]
}